If you are updating multiple values within an array in a Firestore document, you can use the `FieldValue.arrayUnion()` method to add new values to an array or `FieldValue.arrayRemove()` method to remove existing values from an array.

Here is an example of updating an array field using `FieldValue.arrayUnion()`:

```
val dailyExpensesRef = firestore
    .collection("expenses")
    .document("Yearly/Monthly/monthly_expenses/Weekly/weekly_expenses/Daily/daily_expenses")

dailyExpensesRef.update(mapOf(
    "field1" to FieldValue.arrayUnion("new value 1", "new value 2")
)).addOnSuccessListener {
    Log.d(TAG, "Document successfully updated!")
}.addOnFailureListener {
    Log.e(TAG, "Error updating document", it)
}
```

In this example, `dailyExpensesRef` is a reference to the Firestore document representing a day's expenses. The `FieldValue.arrayUnion()` method is used to add new values to an array field called "field1" in the document. In this case, two new values "new value 1" and "new value 2" are added to the "field1" array using a `mapOf` update map.

To remove values from an array, you can use the `FieldValue.arrayRemove()` method instead of `FieldValue.arrayUnion()`. Here is an example:

```
val dailyExpensesRef = firestore
    .collection("expenses")
    .document("Yearly/Monthly/monthly_expenses/Weekly/weekly_expenses/Daily/daily_expenses")

dailyExpensesRef.update(mapOf(
    "field1" to FieldValue.arrayRemove("remove value 1", "remove value 2")
)).addOnSuccessListener {
    Log.d(TAG, "Document successfully updated!")
}.addOnFailureListener {
    Log.e(TAG, "Error updating document", it)
}
```

In this example, `FieldValue.arrayRemove()` is used to remove existing values "remove value 1" and "remove value 2" from an array field called "field1". The `mapOf()` update map is used to pass the updated field value to the `update()` method.
